  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Advances in perinatal care have made it possible to improve the survival of the most immature
      neonates, but at the cost of an increase in the population at risk of developing
      bronchopulmonary dysplasia (BPD). Measures that have attempted to limit the development of
      BPD are not always effective, or related to major side effects. The physiopathological
      factors that are identified in BPD should, in theory, respond to surfactant. Therefore, the
      use of an exogenous surfactant in neonates presenting with pulmonary disease requiring
      mechanical ventilation, leading to a significant risk of BPD, should allow earlier extubation
      and thus promote pulmonary healing and growth.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
